TM17-157/158 — QR/Analytics Access Control & React Hook/Hydration Fixes

Overview

This update addresses two critical issues in the TM17_ASRS project: security gaps in QR management and analytics endpoints, and React hook/hydration errors on the frontend home page.

The QR and analytics endpoints were previously accessible without authentication, allowing unauthorized users to view or manipulate sensitive QR code data and analytics. The frontend home page had React hook warnings, synchronous setState calls in useEffect, and hydration issues that could trigger extra renders or runtime errors.

This update secures backend endpoints and refactors frontend logic to resolve all critical errors and improve overall code quality and performance.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Backend Integration — QR & Analytics Access Control
---------------------------------------------------------------------

Endpoints affected: QR code listing and analytics (route.js, QR endpoints)

Changes made:

- Enforced authentication using `requireAccess` with a minimum access rank of 50
- Early return with 401 status for unauthorized users
- Applied role-based access control for staff/admin users
- Enabled CSRF protection for state-changing operations
- Verified that analytics stats and QR data are only returned to authorized users

Behavior breakdown:

| Condition | Result |
|-----------|--------|
| User not logged in | Endpoint returns 401 Unauthorized |
| User logged in but access rank < 50 | Endpoint returns 401 Unauthorized |
| User logged in with sufficient rank | Endpoint returns QR/analytics data |

Files modified:  
`src/app/api/qr/route.js`  
`src/app/api/analytics/route.js` (if applicable)

---------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Frontend Integration — Home Page React Hook & Hydration Fixes
---------------------------------------------------------------------

Affected component: Home page (page.js)

Changes made:

- Converted `isHydrated` to a lazy `useState` initialization to avoid synchronous setState in useEffect
- Ensured all hooks run unconditionally to fix ESLint hook ordering errors
- Preserved survey initiative selection, navigation cards, and conditional rendering for logged-in and logged-out users

Behavior breakdown:

| Condition | Result |
|-----------|--------|
| Component first renders on server | Returns null until client hydration detected |
| Hooks run | `useEffect` fetches initiatives without triggering extra renders |
| Survey initiative selected | User can navigate to `/survey?initiativeId=` |
| Card hover | Visual effects work without breaking hydration |

Files modified:  
`src/app/page.js`

